is aim is not to provide a grand, unifying theory. Instead, the book guides the reader through the relevant scientific evidence that links neuroscience, music, and meaning. Schulkin considers how music evolved in humans and birds, how music is experienced in relation to aesthetics and mathematics, the role of memory in musical expression, the role of music in child and social development, and the embodied experience of music through dance. He concludes with reflections on music and well-being. Reflections on the Musical Mind is a unique and valuable tour through the current research on the neuroscience of music.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aMusicxOrigin. 0aMusicxPsychological aspects. 0aMusical ability. 7aSCIENCE / Cognitive Science.2bisacsh  aLeonard Meyer.  aWilliams syndrome.  aaction.  aadaptation.  aaesthetics.  aart.  aauditory system.  abirds.  abirdsong.  abrain activation.  abrain.  achild development.  acognition.  acognitive physiology.  acognitive systems.  adance.  adevelopmental disorders.  aembodied cognition.  aemotions.  aepigenetic events.  aevolution.  ahypersocial behaviors.  ahyposocial behaviors.  ainformation molecules.  alanguage.  alifelong learning.  ameaning.  amemory.  amovement.  amusement.  amusic.  amusical expectations.  amusical experience.  amusical expression.  amusical sensibility.  aneurogenesis.  aneuroscience.  aprobabilities.  aproblem solving.  asocial behaviors.  asocial brain.  asocial contact.  asocial development.  asocial harmonies.  asocial instincts.  asong.  asounds.  aspeech.  astability.  asteroid hormones.  asyntax.  atime.  avocal expression.  awell-being.  aworking memory.1 aGjerdingen, Robert O.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gruytert